2,010 A.D.
The Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation funds the third phase of GSK's experimental malaria test vaccine. As a result, 151 African infants die, and 1,048/5,949 develop the following symptoms.
(1) Paralysis

As one might expect, climate is not the only determinant of malaria. A variety of socio-geographical and environmental influences also characterize this disease.

The emergence of malaria is strongly associated with the phenomenon of El Nino circles in a number of countries, India and Venezuela. El Ni√±o may lead to changes, albeit temporary, but severe in the environment, such as temperature swings and sudden floods.

These depend on climatic conditions such as heat, precipitation and humidity.
The ideal temperature for malaria-carrying mosquitoes is 15 to 30 degrees Celsius. Temperature exerts various influences on mosquito survival and reproduction rates.

This implies that there is a specific range of climatic conditions under which a pathogen and a vector can live, reproduce, and infect the host organisms. Vector-borne diseases such as malaria have characteristics that determine the ability to transmit diseases.

Malaria in particular is vulnerable to changes in the environment as both the causative agent of the disease Plasmodium and its vector, mosquitoes, lack the necessary mechanism to regulate temperature and fluid levels.

vector-borne diseases such as malaria, dengue fever and leishmaniasis represent the strongest causal relationship, with malaria in particular, which kills nearly 300,000 children annually, poses the greatest threat.
